### PHP Form Required Fields

Required fields ensure that users provide necessary information before form submission.

### Checking Required Fields

```php
<?php
$nameErr = $emailErr = $genderErr = "";
$name = $email = $gender = "";
$valid = true;

if ($_SERVER["REQUEST_METHOD"] == "POST") {
    if (empty($_POST["name"])) {
        $nameErr = "Name is required";
        $valid = false;
    } else {
        $name = htmlspecialchars(trim($_POST["name"]));
    }

    if (empty($_POST["email"])) {
        $emailErr = "Email is required";
        $valid = false;
    } else {
        $email = htmlspecialchars(trim($_POST["email"]));
    }

    if (empty($_POST["gender"])) {
        $genderErr = "Gender is required";
        $valid = false;
    } else {
        $gender = $_POST["gender"];
    }

    if ($valid) {
        echo "Form submitted successfully!";
    }
}
?>
```

### HTML Required Attribute

```html
<input type="text" name="name" required>
```

Note: HTML5 `required` attribute provides client-side validation but can be bypassed. Always validate on the server.

### Common Required Field Handling

| Field Type | Validation |
|------------|------------|
| Text input | `empty(trim($value))` |
| Checkbox | `!isset($_POST["agree"])` |
| Radio group | `empty($_POST["gender"])` |
| Select dropdown | `$_POST["country"] === ""` |
| File upload | `$_FILES["file"]["error"] === 4` |

> **Key Point:** Use a `$valid` flag to track overall form validity and only process the form when all validations pass.
